Here's the full Claude Code prompt:

---

```
# INKFRAME — AI VIDEO CREATOR: FULL IMPLEMENTATION SPEC
# For Claude Code — Read this entire document before writing any code.

---

## WHAT YOU ARE BUILDING

Inkframe is an AI-powered animated explainer video creator with:
- Multi-layer composited scenes (canvas2d + D3 + Three.js + SVG + Lottie + HTML per scene)
- An agentic chat interface where users talk to specialized sub-agents
- WebVideoCreator + FFmpeg export pipeline for real MP4
- Interactive publish mode (hosted iframe embed)
- Hand-drawn whiteboard aesthetic via Canvas2D + Rough.js
- Pre-drawn asset library (150 assets)
- Scene graph editor for branching (interactive mode)

The core loop:
  User chats with agent →
  Agent reads world state →
  Agent calls tools (structured operations) →
  Scene HTML regenerates →
  Preview updates live →
  User iterates

---

## PART 1 — WORLD STATE (THE AGENT'S "CODEBASE")

This is the single source of truth. Everything the agent reads
and modifies. Store in Zustand + persist to SQLite.

```ts
interface WorldState {
  project: Project
  scenes: Scene[]
  sceneGraph: SceneGraph
  selectedSceneId: string | null
  history: Snapshot[]        // for undo/redo
  historyIndex: number
}

interface Project {
  id: string
  name: string
  outputMode: 'mp4' | 'interactive'
  globalStyle: GlobalStyle
  mp4Settings: MP4Settings
  interactiveSettings: InteractiveSettings
}

interface GlobalStyle {
  palette: [string, string, string, string]  // exactly 4 hex colors
  font: 'Caveat' | 'DM Mono' | 'Georgia' | 'monospace'
  roughnessLevel: number    // 0-3
  strokeWidth: number       // 1-5
  bgColor: string
}

// THE KEY CHANGE: scenes have LAYERS not a single type
interface Scene {
  id: string
  name: string
  duration: number          // seconds
  bgColor: string
  thumbnail: string | null
  transition: TransitionConfig
  layers: SceneLayer[]      // ordered bottom→top
  interactions: InteractionElement[]
  audioLayer: AudioLayer | null
  videoLayer: VideoLayer | null
}

// Each layer is independently typed and rendered
type SceneLayer =
  | Canvas2DLayer
  | SVGLayer
  | D3Layer
  | ThreeLayer
  | LottieLayer
  | HTMLLayer
  | AssetLayer

interface BaseLayer {
  id: string
  label: string             // human name: "main diagram", "background sketch"
  type: LayerType
  visible: boolean
  opacity: number           // 0-1
  blendMode: 'normal' | 'multiply' | 'screen' | 'overlay'
  zIndex: number
  // Timing within the scene
  startAt: number           // seconds into scene when layer begins
  duration: number | null   // null = runs to end of scene
  // Generated content
  generatedCode: string     // the actual JS/SVG/HTML that runs
  // Structured elements within this layer (for surgical editing)
  elements: SceneElement[]
  // Generation metadata
  prompt: string            // what was asked to generate this layer
  generatedAt: string
  modelUsed: string
}

interface Canvas2DLayer extends BaseLayer {
  type: 'canvas2d'
  roughnessLevel: number    // can override global
  seed: number              // for deterministic randomness
}

interface SVGLayer extends BaseLayer {
  type: 'svg'
  roughnessLevel: number
  viewBox: string
}

interface D3Layer extends BaseLayer {
  type: 'd3'
  data: any                 // the data driving the visualization
  chartType: string         // 'bar' | 'line' | 'force' | etc
}

interface ThreeLayer extends BaseLayer {
  type: 'three'
  cameraType: 'perspective' | 'orthographic'
}

interface LottieLayer extends BaseLayer {
  type: 'lottie'
  source: string            // URL or inline JSON
}

interface HTMLLayer extends BaseLayer {
  type: 'html'
  // Pure HTML/CSS for titles, captions, text overlays
}

interface AssetLayer extends BaseLayer {
  type: 'assets'
  placements: AssetPlacement[]
}

// Structured elements within a layer (what the agent edits surgically)
type SceneElement =
  | TextElement
  | LineElement
  | ShapeElement
  | ArrowElement
  | AssetElement
  | GroupElement

// (full element interfaces as defined previously)
// Each has: id, label, position, color, timing, etc.
```

---

## PART 2 — THE AGENT SYSTEM

### 2.1 Agent Architecture

Four specialized agents. Each has a narrow scope, its own
system prompt, and its own tool subset. The user chooses
which agent they're talking to OR lets the router decide.

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│           CHAT INTERFACE                │
│  Agent selector + model selector +      │
│  scene context + tool filter            │
└──────────────┬──────────────────────────┘
               │
    ┌──────────▼──────────┐
    │   ROUTER AGENT      │  (only if no agent selected)
    │   Classifies intent │
    │   Routes to agent   │
    └──────────┬──────────┘
               │
    ┌──────────┼──────────┬──────────────┐
    ▼          ▼          ▼              ▼
┌───────┐ ┌───────┐ ┌─────────┐ ┌──────────┐
│DIREC- │ │SCENE  │ │ EDITOR  │ │DIRECTOR  │
│TOR    │ │MAKER  │ │ AGENT   │ │ AGENT    │
│AGENT  │ │AGENT  │ │         │ │          │
│Plans  │ │Genera-│ │Surgical │ │Global    │
│multi- │ │tes    │ │edits to │ │style,    │
│scene  │ │layers │ │elements │ │timing,   │
│videos │ │for    │ │& layers │ │transitions│
│       │ │scenes │ │         │ │          │
└───────┘ └───────┘ └─────────┘ └──────────┘
```

**Router Agent** (small/fast, used only when no agent selected):
- Reads user message + current world state summary
- Decides: which agent should handle this?
- Returns: { agent: 'director'|'scene-maker'|'editor'|'director' }
- Uses cheapest/fastest model (haiku or local)
- Never visible to user

**Director Agent**:
- Handles: "make me a 5-scene video about X"
- Plans the full video: scene count, scene topics, layer composition per scene
- Creates scene stubs in world state
- Hands off individual scene generation to Scene Maker
- Thinks about narrative arc, pacing, transitions
- Tool access: create_scene, delete_scene, reorder_scenes,
  set_transition, set_project_settings, plan_scenes

**Scene Maker Agent**:
- Handles: "generate scene 2" or "draw a diagram of X"
- Decides layer composition for the scene
- Generates code for each layer (may call sub-generators per layer type)
- Updates scene.layers with generated content
- Tool access: add_layer, generate_layer_code, set_scene_duration,
  set_scene_background, search_assets, add_asset_placement

**Editor Agent**:
- Handles: "make the cloud bigger", "change title to blue",
  "move the arrow down", "the chart is too cluttered"
- Makes SURGICAL edits to existing elements
- NEVER regenerates a whole scene unless explicitly asked
- Reads element list, identifies target elements, patches specific fields
- Tool access: edit_element, move_element, resize_element,
  delete_element, add_element, adjust_timing, set_roughness,
  reorder_elements, edit_layer_code (targeted code patch)

**Director of Photography Agent** (named to match film terminology):
- Handles: global style changes, color palette, transitions,
  timing adjustments across all scenes, roughness, fonts
- "Make the whole video feel more professional"
- "Add smooth transitions everywhere"
- "Change the color scheme to blues and grays"
- Tool access: set_global_style, set_transition (all scenes),
  set_roughness (all scenes), reorder_scenes, set_scene_duration (all)

### 2.2 User-Controlled Agent Selection

THE KEY FEATURE: users can bypass routing and talk directly
to any agent. They can also control:
- Which model the selected agent uses
- Which scene gets context injected
- Which layer types (tools) are available

This is exposed in the chat UI as an Agent Control Panel.

### 2.3 Knowledge Injection (Remotion-style)

Each agent gets a base system prompt + dynamically injected
rule files based on context. Never inject all rules at once.

Rule files (markdown, injected when relevant):
- rules/canvas2d.md      — canvas renderer API, all functions
- rules/svg.md           — SVG animation patterns, stroke-dashoffset
- rules/d3.md            — D3 v7 patterns, chart types, data binding
- rules/three.md         — Three.js r128, what's available, what's not
- rules/lottie.md        — Lottie integration, playback control
- rules/assets.md        — asset library index, how to reference assets
- rules/rough.md         — Rough.js integration, roughness values
- rules/composition.md   — layer ordering, blending, timing
- rules/transitions.md   — transition types, FFmpeg xfade params
- rules/interactions.md  — hotspot, choice, quiz, gate elements
- rules/timing.md        — animation sequencing, delays, pacing
- rules/text.md          — text rendering rules (NEVER char-by-char)
- rules/export.md        — WVC export constraints, determinism rules

Injection logic:
- Canvas2D layer requested → inject rules/canvas2d.md + rules/rough.md
- D3 layer → inject rules/d3.md
- Three.js → inject rules/three.md
- Any layer → always inject rules/timing.md + rules/text.md
- Interactive mode → inject rules/interactions.md
- Transition edit → inject rules/transitions.md
- Asset placement → inject rules/assets.md

### 2.4 Decision-Time Guidance (Replit-style)

Don't front-load all rules into the system prompt.
Inject guidance at the moment of decision.

Before generating a canvas2d layer:
  "You are generating a Canvas2D layer.
   Available roughness: {scene.roughnessLevel}.
   Canvas size: 1920x1080. Available assets: {relevantAssets}.
   Elements already on other layers in this scene: {otherLayerElements}
   so avoid overlapping with: {occupiedRegions}."

Before making an edit:
  "You are editing element '{element.label}' (id: {element.id}).
   Current values: {currentValues}.
   Other elements in this scene: {siblingElements}.
   Only change the fields listed in your tool call."

This keeps context lean and decision-focused.

---

## PART 3 — TOOL DEFINITIONS

All tools are typed TypeScript functions on the server.
The agent calls them via Anthropic tool use API.
Tools execute, update world state, trigger HTML regeneration,
trigger preview reload.

### Core scene tools:
```ts
create_scene(prompt, position?, duration?)
delete_scene(sceneId)
duplicate_scene(sceneId)
reorder_scenes(sceneId, newIndex)
set_scene_duration(sceneId, duration)
set_scene_background(sceneId, color)
set_transition(sceneId, type, duration)
```

### Layer tools:
```ts
add_layer(sceneId, layerType, label, prompt)
// Generates code for the layer and adds it

remove_layer(sceneId, layerId)
reorder_layer(sceneId, layerId, newZIndex)
set_layer_opacity(sceneId, layerId, opacity)
set_layer_visibility(sceneId, layerId, visible)
set_layer_timing(sceneId, layerId, startAt, duration)
regenerate_layer(sceneId, layerId, newPrompt?)
// Regenerates a specific layer's code only

patch_layer_code(sceneId, layerId, oldCode, newCode)
// Surgical code edit — like str_replace in Claude Code
// For editor agent making targeted changes
```

### Element tools:
```ts
add_element(sceneId, layerId, element)
edit_element(sceneId, layerId, elementId, changes)
delete_element(sceneId, layerId, elementId)
move_element(sceneId, layerId, elementId, x, y)
resize_element(sceneId, layerId, elementId, width, height)
reorder_element(sceneId, layerId, elementId, direction)
adjust_element_timing(sceneId, layerId, elementId, delay, duration)
```

### Asset tools:
```ts
search_assets(query, category?)
// Returns matching assets from library

place_asset(sceneId, layerId, assetId, x, y, width, height, opts)
remove_asset(sceneId, layerId, placementId)
```

### Global tools:
```ts
set_global_style(changes)  // palette, font, roughness, etc
set_all_transitions(type, duration)
set_roughness_all(level)
plan_scenes(topic, sceneCount, style)
// Returns a scene plan array, doesn't execute yet
```

### Media tools:
```ts
set_audio_layer(sceneId, audioConfig)
set_video_layer(sceneId, videoConfig)
search_images(query)  // Unsplash API
place_image(sceneId, layerId, imageUrl, x, y, width, height)
```

### Interaction tools (interactive mode only):
```ts
add_interaction(sceneId, interactionElement)
edit_interaction(sceneId, interactionId, changes)
connect_scenes(fromSceneId, toSceneId, condition)
```

### Export/publish tools:
```ts
export_mp4(settings)
publish_interactive(settings)
```

---

## PART 4 — AGENT CONTROL PANEL UI

This is the critical UI feature. Sits above the chat input.
Collapsed by default, expands when user clicks "⚙ Agent Settings".

### 4.1 Agent Selector

Five pills, one selectable at a time (or "Auto"):

```
[ Auto ] [ Director ] [ Scene Maker ] [ Editor ] [ DoP ]
```

- Auto: router decides (default)
- Selecting an agent: bypasses router, sends directly to that agent
- Selected agent's name appears in chat messages from that agent
- Color-coded: Director=purple, SceneMaker=blue, Editor=green, DoP=orange

When an agent is selected:
- Its specific tool subset is active
- Its specific knowledge rules are always injected
- The model selector shows that agent's default model
- The user can override the model

### 4.2 Model Selector

Per-agent model override. Dropdown:

```
Model: [ claude-sonnet-4-20250514 ▾ ]
         claude-opus-4-20250514
         claude-haiku-4-5-20251001
         (local) qwen2.5-coder:14b    ← if Ollama running
         (local) llama3.1:8b          ← if Ollama running
```

Default per agent:
- Router: haiku (fast, cheap classification)
- Director: sonnet (complex planning)
- Scene Maker: sonnet (code generation)
- Editor: haiku or sonnet (depends on edit complexity)
- DoP: haiku (mostly simple parameter changes)

User override persists per agent until changed.

Local models: ping localhost:11434 on load to detect Ollama.
If running, fetch model list and add to dropdown.
Local models get a "(local)" prefix and a lightning bolt icon.

### 4.3 Scene Context Selector

```
Scene context: [ All scenes ▾ ]
                 All scenes
                 ─────────────
                 Scene 1: Introduction
                 Scene 2: The Problem
                 Scene 3: Our Solution
                 ...
```

Default: "All scenes" — agent gets summary of all scenes.

When a specific scene is selected:
- Agent gets FULL detail of that scene: all layers, all elements,
  all generated code, all asset placements
- Agent gets SUMMARY only of other scenes (name + duration + prompt)
- This keeps context lean while giving full detail where needed
- The scene also gets highlighted in the scene list panel
- Chat messages referencing this scene auto-highlight relevant layers

Use case: "I want to talk to the Editor about specifically scene 3"
→ Select Editor agent + Scene 3 context
→ Editor gets full scene 3 data, can make precise surgical edits

### 4.4 Tool Filter (Layer Type Filter)

The key specialization feature. A set of toggleable chips:

```
Active tools:
[✓ Canvas2D] [✓ SVG] [✓ D3] [✓ Three.js] [✓ Lottie] [✓ Assets]
[✓ Audio] [✓ Video] [✓ Interactions] [✓ Transitions]
```

Toggling a tool OFF:
- Removes it from the agent's available tool list
- Injects a constraint into the agent's system prompt:
  "You may NOT use {tool} layers. If the user requests something
   that would normally use {tool}, achieve it using the available
   tools instead."
- The agent adapts: if Three.js is off and user asks for 3D,
  the agent might fake it with Canvas2D perspective drawing

Use cases:
- Designer who only wants hand-drawn style: turn off D3, Three.js, Lottie
- Data analyst who only wants charts: select only D3, HTML
- Quick sketch mode: Canvas2D only
- Interactive-only: disable everything except Interactions
- Simple mode for non-technical clients: Canvas2D + Assets + HTML only

Preset buttons below the chips:
```
Presets: [Whiteboard] [Data Story] [3D Showcase] [Simple] [Custom]
```

Whiteboard: Canvas2D + SVG + Assets + HTML (no D3/Three/Lottie)
Data Story: D3 + HTML + Canvas2D annotations
3D Showcase: Three.js + HTML + Canvas2D minimal
Simple: Canvas2D + HTML only
Custom: whatever the user set

### 4.5 How Tool Filter Updates Agent Context

When tools are filtered, three things change:

1. Tool definitions sent to Claude API are filtered
   (only active tool types appear in the tools array)

2. System prompt gets a constraint block injected:
   ```
   AVAILABLE LAYER TYPES: canvas2d, svg, html
   DISABLED LAYER TYPES: d3, three, lottie, assets
   Never suggest or generate disabled layer types.
   Achieve all visual goals using only the available types.
   ```

3. Knowledge rule injection is filtered:
   Only rule files for active types are injected.
   This keeps context lean.

### 4.6 Agent Control Panel — Complete UI

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ ⚙ Agent Settings                              [−]   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Agent:                                              │
│ [Auto] [Director] [Scene Maker] [Editor] [DoP]     │
│                                                     │
│ Model:  [claude-sonnet-4-20250514        ▾]        │
│                                                     │
│ Scene context:  [All scenes              ▾]        │
│                                                     │
│ Active tools:                                       │
│ [✓ Canvas2D] [✓ SVG] [✗ D3] [✗ Three.js]         │
│ [✓ Assets] [✓ HTML] [✗ Lottie]                    │
│ [✓ Audio] [✗ Video] [✓ Transitions]               │
│                                                     │
│ Presets: [Whiteboard] [Data] [3D] [Simple]        │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

